{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17590559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17590559"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15202"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15202"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.41,0.04,0.04,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67318"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7893"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52770"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5366"},{"type":"tags","id":"8131"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22540"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67318"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Gleason scoring system is used to grade prostate adenocarcinoma based on its microscopic appearance and architectural patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the microscopic appearance of prostate cancer with a Gleason score of 6?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cribriform masses with irregular edges","Poorly formed glands with irregular borders","Sheets of cells without glandular formation","Single cells infiltrating stroma","Well-formed, uniform glands with distinct borders"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA Gleason score of 6 (3+3) represents a well-differentiated prostate cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EWell-formed, uniform glands with distinct borders\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of Gleason pattern 3, which when present as the two predominant patterns results in a score of 6.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoorly formed glands with irregular borders\u003C/strong\u003E represent Gleason pattern 4. \u003Cstrong\u003ESheets of cells without glandular formation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle cells infiltrating stroma\u003C/strong\u003E are features of Gleason pattern 5, the most aggressive pattern. \u003Cstrong\u003ECribriform masses with irregular edges\u003C/strong\u003E are also characteristic of Gleason pattern 4.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe Gleason score is calculated by adding the grades of the two most predominant patterns seen in the specimen. Each pattern is graded from 1-5, with higher numbers indicating more aggressive and less differentiated disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gleason score 6 prostate cancer shows well-formed, uniform glands with distinct borders and minimal invasion","The Gleason scoring system grades prostate cancer from 1-5 based on glandular architecture and differentiation","Gleason score is calculated by adding the two most predominant pattern grades seen in the specimen"],"references":["Tagai EK, Miller SM, Kutikov A, Diefenbach MA, Gor RA, Al-Saleem T, Chen DYT, Fleszar S, Roy G. Prostate Cancer Patients\u0027 Understanding of the Gleason Scoring System: Implications for Shared Decision-Making. J Cancer Educ. 2019 Jun;34(3):441-445. doi: 10.1007/s13187-018-1320-1. PMID: 29333577; PMCID: PMC6557691.","Munjal A, Leslie SW. Gleason Score. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553178/","Humphrey PA. Histopathology of Prostate Cancer. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2017 Oct 3;7(10):a030411. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a030411. PMID: 28389514; PMCID: PMC5629988.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52770"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15202"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52770"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T20:10:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T20:10:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7893"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67318"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)",